WEBVTT

00:21.120 --> 00:22.440
III.

00:23.100 --> 00:24.600
ATTACK BY STRATEGYM

00:25.600 --> 00:26.740
Sun Tzu said,

00:27.060 --> 00:44.900
In the practical art of war, the best thing of all is to take the enemy's country whole and intact. To shatter and destroy it is not so good. So too it is better to recapture an army entire than to destroy it, to capture a regiment, a detachment, or a company entire than to destroy them.

00:45.540 --> 00:54.680
Hence to fight and conquer in all your battles is not supreme excellence. Supreme excellence consists in breaking the enemy's resistance without fighting.

00:55.780 --> 01:10.620
Thus the highest form of generalship is to balk the enemy's plans. The next best is to prevent the junction of the enemy's forces. The next in order is to attack the enemy's army in the field. And the worst policy of all is to besiege walled cities.

01:11.460 --> 01:26.340
The rule is not to besiege walled cities if it can possibly be avoided. The preparation of mantlets, movable shelters, and various implements of war will take up three whole months, and the piling up of mounds against the walls will take three months more.

01:26.960 --> 01:41.860
The general, unable to control his irritation, will launch his men to the assault like swarming ants, with the result that one third of his men are slain, while the town still remains untaken. Such are the disastrous effects of a siege.

01:43.060 --> 01:53.780
Therefore the skillful leader subdues the enemy's troops without any fighting. He captures their cities without laying siege to them. He overthrows their kingdom without lengthy operations in the field.

01:54.400 --> 02:05.060
With his forces intact, he will dispute the mastery of the empire, and thus, without losing a man, his triumph will be complete. This is the method of attacking by stratagem.

02:05.800 --> 02:26.320
It is the rule in war if our forces are ten to the enemy's one, to surround him, if five to one, to attack him, if twice as numerous, to divide our army into two. If equally matched, we can offer battle. If slightly inferior in numbers, we can avoid the enemy. If quite unequal in every way, we can flee from him.

02:27.060 --> 02:33.980
Hence, though an obstinate fight may be made by a small force, in the end it must be captured by the larger force.

02:34.940 --> 02:44.080
Now the general is the bulwark of the state. If the bulwark is complete at all points, the state will be strong. If the bulwark is defective, the state will be weak.

02:44.080 --> 02:48.380
There are three ways in which a ruler can bring misfortune upon his army.

02:49.380 --> 02:57.100
One, by commanding the army to advance or to retreat, being ignorant of the fact that it cannot obey. This is called hobbling the army.

02:57.940 --> 03:08.640
Two, by attempting to govern an army in the same way as he administers a kingdom, being ignorant of the conditions which obtain in an army. This causes restlessness in the soldier's minds.

03:09.520 --> 03:20.760
Three, by employing the officers of his army without discrimination through ignorance of the military principle of adaptation to circumstances. This shakes the confidence of the soldiers.

03:21.920 --> 03:31.200
But when the army is restless and distrustful, trouble is sure to come from the other feudal princes. This is simply bringing anarchy into the army and flinging victory away.

03:32.080 --> 03:35.580
Thus we may know that there are five essentials for victory.

03:36.280 --> 03:40.900
One, he will win who knows when to fight and when not to fight.

03:41.440 --> 03:46.380
Two, he will win who knows how to handle both superior and inferior forces.

03:47.360 --> 03:52.260
Three, he will win whose army is animated by the same spirit throughout all its ranks.

03:53.240 --> 03:58.380
Four, he will win who, prepared himself, waits to take the enemy unprepared.

03:59.120 --> 04:05.060
Five, he will win who has military capacity and is not interfered with by the sovereign.

04:06.480 --> 04:12.640
Hence the saying, if you know the enemy and know yourself, you need not fear the result of a hundred battles.

04:13.220 --> 04:18.660
If you know yourself but not the enemy, for every victory gained you will also suffer a defeat.

04:19.300 --> 04:23.900
If you know neither the enemy nor yourself, you will succumb in every battle.

04:24.660 --> 04:27.600
End of part three.

04:28.580 --> 04:31.480
Part four. Tactical dispositions.

04:32.720 --> 04:40.660
Sun Tzu said, the good fighters of old first put themselves beyond the possibility of defeat and then waited for an opportunity of defeating the enemy.

04:41.540 --> 04:49.340
To secure ourselves against defeat lies in our own hands, but the opportunity of defeating the enemy is provided by the enemy himself.

04:49.340 --> 04:55.960
Thus the good fighter is able to secure himself against defeat but cannot make certain of defeating the enemy.

04:56.720 --> 05:01.420
Hence the saying, one may know how to conquer without being able to do it.

05:02.340 --> 05:05.120
Security against defeat implies defensive tactics.

05:05.680 --> 05:08.380
Ability to defeat the enemy means taking the offensive.

05:09.420 --> 05:15.360
Standing on the defensive indicates insufficient strength, attacking a superabundance of strength.

05:16.280 --> 05:20.900
The general who is skilled in defense hides in the most secret recesses of the earth.

05:21.440 --> 05:25.640
He who is skilled and attacked flashes forth from the topmost heights of heaven.

05:26.700 --> 05:32.140
Thus on the one hand we have ability to protect ourselves, on the other a victory that is complete.

05:33.220 --> 05:38.660
To see victory only when it is within the ken of the common herd is not the acme of excellence.

05:38.660 --> 05:45.300
Neither is it the acme of excellence if you fight and conquer and the whole empire says, well done.

05:46.700 --> 05:49.840
To lift an autumn hare is no sign of great strength.

05:50.440 --> 05:53.260
To see the sun and moon is no sign of sharp sight.

05:54.220 --> 05:57.380
To hear the noise of thunder is no sign of a quick ear.

05:58.260 --> 06:04.320
What the ancients called a clever fighter is one who not only wins but excels in winning with ease.

06:04.320 --> 06:09.880
Hence his victories bring him neither reputation for wisdom nor credit for courage.

06:11.000 --> 06:13.580
He wins his battles by making no mistakes.

06:14.280 --> 06:20.780
Making no mistakes is what establishes the certainty of victory, for it means conquering an enemy that is already defeated.

06:21.560 --> 06:29.220
Hence the skillful fighter puts himself into a position which makes defeat impossible and does not miss the moment for defeating the enemy.

06:30.060 --> 06:35.780
Thus it is that in war the victorious strategist only seeks battle after the victory has been won,

06:36.060 --> 06:40.840
whereas he who is destined to defeat first fights and afterwards looks for victory.

06:42.500 --> 06:47.620
The consummate leader cultivates the moral law and strictly adheres to method and discipline.

06:48.300 --> 06:50.840
Thus it is in his power to control success.

06:51.620 --> 07:04.360
In respect of military method we have firstly measurement, secondly estimation of quantity, thirdly calculation, fourthly balancing of chances, fifthly victory.

07:05.440 --> 07:07.500
Measurement owes its existence to earth.

07:08.180 --> 07:16.800
Estimation of quantity to measurement, calculation to estimation of quantity, balancing of chances to calculation, and victory to balancing of chances.

07:16.800 --> 07:23.800
A victorious army opposed to a routed one is as a pound's weight placed in the scale against a single grain.

07:25.000 --> 07:31.580
The onrush of a conquering force is like the bursting of pent-up waters into a chasm a thousand fathoms deep.

